Before analyse it, let us make a bit explanation about all columns that interests this project¶

  • tweet_id : represents the primary key of every tweet;
  • timestamp : UTC time when this Tweet was created, it's called also created_at on tweet object
  • source : is the url link (href) that allows user the post of the tweet;
  • text : is message found inside of the tweet
  • rating_numerator : Dog numerator rate
  • raiting_denominator : Dog denominator rate
  • name : represents the name of the dog
  • doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo, are chronological dog personnality

Observation :¶

  • The doggo, flooter, pupper, puppo should be in the same column
  • The source variable contains invalids url

#function that return the number of None entries in variables
def noneValueInColomn(dataFrame, nameColumn):
    count=0
    for entrie in dataFrame:
        if(entrie=='None'):
            count += 1
    if(count >0):
        print('{} entries found,  where the variable {} present a none value'.format(count, nameColumn)) 
    return count

Quality issues¶

  • We should have 5000 or more tweets, but we only have 2356 entries: => completeness problem
  • There are 3 entries concerned by rating_denominator and 440 for rating_numerator are less than 10; in the tweet archive
  • the timestamp variable is an object, linked to a string, whereas it must have a datetime format: validity problem
  • Similarly, tweet_id will be considered in the analysis as a non-int but a string, which avoids statistical errors
  • some extended URLs are null, others contain several redundant links => recurring problem
  • There are 745 entries that contain NONE, name variable value and correct values ​​must be uppercase
  • Source variable contains error URL: => valid problem
  • doggo, flooter, pupper, puppo are invalid, entries contain 9775 none instead of NAN or the correct entry
  • we should have 5000 or more tweets, but we only have 2356 entries
  • the timestamp variable is an object, linked to a string, whereas it must have the datetime format: => validity problem
  • 440 tweets entries contain a value less than the minimum value (10) required for each rating_numerator
  • we have retweet variables which are nullable as long as the tweet is not retweeted which are: retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id, retweeted_status_timestamp, in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id
  • p1,p2,p3 in the prediction dataset must be lowercase

Tidiness issues¶

  • doggo, flooter, pupper, puppo variables as depicted above, can be combined in one column in df_archive_enhanced
  • Data set of old and additional tweets, should be clearly combined for interesting analysis

def parse_values(x):
    if x == "None" or x== "NaN":
        return "NaN"
    else:
        return (str(x[0]).upper()+str(x[1:]).lower())

Creating a new column instead of 3 for dog's personnality¶

In [1091]:
#defining the function witch receives the row
def dog_growth(entrie):
    lstPersonnality = []
    if entrie['doggo'] == 'doggo':
        lstPersonnality.append('doggo')
    if entrie['floofer'] == 'floofer':
        lstPersonnality.append('floofer')
    if entrie['pupper'] == 'pupper':
        lstPersonnality.append('pupper')
    if entrie['puppo'] == 'puppo':
        lstPersonnality.append('puppo')   
    
    if len(lstPersonnality) < 1:
        #if all dogs are None, then
        entrie['dog_growth'] = 'NaN'
    else:
        entrie['dog_growth'] = ' and '.join(lstPersonnality)
    return entrie

def plotResult(p1,pConf):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
